  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't something I've ever really encountered myself, but I've seen it play out in the shop where I work. When folks from my neighborhood or other communities start talking about how hard it is to get into tech fields, they often mention that kids from certain backgrounds feel like they're failing before they even start. I've heard stories from my own kids who've been told they're not cut out for engineering or computer science. It's a real thing—when you're told you don't belong, it affects your performance. I know from my own experience as a mechanic that confidence comes from knowing you can do the job. If a kid thinks they're not good at math, they might avoid it altogether, even if they could. The problem isn't just about the stereotype itself—it's about how it makes people feel. We need to address it by making sure everyone has the same chance to learn without fear. In my shop, I try to encourage kids to see themselves as capable, not limited by what they've been told. That means giving them hands-on experience, showing them real-world applications, and letting them know they can succeed if they work hard. I've noticed that when kids feel supported, they perform better. So yes, we should address stereotype threat in STEM. It's not about fixing the problem but helping people believe they can do it. If we do that, more kids from all backgrounds could thrive in these fields.",
